WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:12.504
Every time the simulator runs, it boils thousands of
evaluations down to a single row of numbers. Learning to
read this row is really the whole skill.

2
00:00:13.104 --> 00:00:32.208
Start with the pass and bust pair. Pass Rate is how often
you hit target before busting. Your headline odds. Above
sixty percent and the move clears these rules comfortably.
Bust Rate is how often you failed, and it even splits the
reason. Drawdown, or daily loss. If daily busts dominate,
your size is too big for the rule.

3
00:00:32.808 --> 00:00:44.376
Still Active is the share of runs that hadn't passed or
busted when the window closed. They simply ran out of
days. A big still-active number is a warning. The move is
too slow for this evaluation's time limit.

4
00:00:44.976 --> 00:00:57.336
Days to Pass is how long a typical winning run takes. Use
it to budget the evaluation, and to sanity-check against
your max-days rule. If days to pass is creeping up near
your limit, you're cutting it dangerously close.

5
00:00:57.936 --> 00:01:12.600
Expected dollars End is the average ending balance across
every single attempt. Passes and busts together. This is
the honest one. A move can pass eighty percent of the time
and still post a weak expected end, if the busts that do
happen are expensive.

6
00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:25.056
The bar underneath shows the split at a glance. Green
passed, red busted. And the line below it grounds the
whole thing in reality, telling you what actually happened
on your real trades, not just in the simulation.

7
00:01:25.656 --> 00:01:33.528
Five numbers, one row. Read them together and you know,
before you spend a single cent, whether this evaluation is
even worth attempting.
